# Deployment Rules

These rules govern how code is reviewed, merged, and deployed in this repository.
They apply to all contributors, including AI coding assistants.

---

## Branch Model

| Branch    | Purpose                          | Protected |
|-----------|----------------------------------|-----------|
| `main`    | Production — deployed automatically on merge | Yes — no direct push |
| `staging` | Integration target — deployed automatically on merge | Yes — PRs required |
| `feature/*` / `fix/*` | Developer working branches — deleted after merge | No |

---

## The Rules

### 1. No direct pushes to `main` or `staging`
All changes must arrive via pull request. Branch protection enforces this.

### 2. All work branches target `staging`
Open PRs from your feature or fix branch into `staging`, not `main`.

### 3. PRs require at least one approval
A reviewer other than the author must approve before merging.
For small teams: if no review is possible within 48 hours and the change is low-risk,
the author may self-merge with a note explaining why.

### 4. Staging is always deployable
Do not merge broken or half-finished work into `staging`.
Use a Draft PR to share work-in-progress without triggering a review or merge.

### 5. Production is promoted from staging, not deployed directly
To release to production, open a PR from `staging` → `main`.
Get one approval. Merge. GitHub Actions handles the rest.

### 6. Hotfixes are the only exception
If production is broken and urgent:
- Branch from `main` (e.g. `hotfix/brief-description`)
- PR directly into `main` — bypass staging if necessary
- After merging, open a follow-up PR from `main` → `staging` to re-sync

### 7. Never commit secrets
No passwords, API keys, tokens, or credentials belong in the repository.
Use GitHub Actions Secrets for CI/CD credentials.
Use server-side environment variables for runtime secrets.

### 8. Delete branches after merging
Keep the branch list clean. GitHub can be configured to do this automatically.

---

## What Happens on Merge

| Event              | Docker image tag       | Deploys to        |
|--------------------|------------------------|-------------------|
| Push to `staging`  | `:staging`             | Staging server    |
| Merge to `main`    | `:latest` + `:vX.Y.Z`  | Production server |

---

## PR Checklist

Before opening a PR, confirm:
- [ ] The branch is up to date with `staging` (or `main` for hotfixes)
- [ ] The change does what the PR title says
- [ ] No secrets are included
- [ ] The app runs locally (or in a dev environment) without errors
- [ ] The PR description explains *what* changed and *why*

---

## Merging Strategy

Use **Squash and Merge** for feature/fix PRs into `staging`.
Use **Merge Commit** for the `staging` → `main` release PR (preserves history).

---

## Notes for AI Assistants

- Never suggest pushing directly to `main` or `staging`
- Always recommend opening a PR with a clear description
- Treat secrets in code as a hard blocker — flag immediately, do not proceed
- When helping with CI/CD changes, respect the two-workflow model:
  one workflow for staging, one for production
- If asked to "deploy" something, clarify whether staging or production is intended

## Versioning

This project uses semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH).

The canonical version lives in `VERSION` (a plain text file in the root).

When opening a release PR (staging → main):
- Bump the version following semver: patch for fixes, minor for new features, major for breaking changes
- The merge to main will automatically tag the commit and build a versioned Docker image

The version is available to the application as the `APP_VERSION` environment variable.
